<div id="review_49037062" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/49037062" />
    <a title="Collin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/962544-collin"><img alt="Collin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1215464714p2/962544.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/49037062?book_show_action=true">Mar 12, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Collin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Collin" href="/user/show/962544-collin">Collin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer49037062&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer49037062" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14643545149161054472">This was a good book. It was very real, and they didn&apos;t need explenations for how things worked, because that&apos;s just how life is. I liked it! It was a really fast read, though. But they left out everything with Devon! They had a big hidden story with Devon and how he took the picture of Nina&apos;s hand and how they thought he spread the rumar but he didn&apos;t and though in the beginning he was thought of as annoying, he was actually really nice and the last time he was mentioned was new years eve when </span>
  <span id="freeText14643545149161054472" style="display:none">This was a good book. It was very real, and they didn't need explenations for how things worked, because that's just how life is. I liked it! It was a really fast read, though. But they left out everything with Devon! They had a big hidden story with Devon and how he took the picture of Nina's hand and how they thought he spread the rumar but he didn't and though in the beginning he was thought of as annoying, he was actually really nice and the last time he was mentioned was new years eve when Nina was drunk and wanted to kiss him and the author kinda foreshadowed that he liked her/might ask her out. It annoys me how they just kinda dropped his story and never mentioned him again. I also thought Parker got kinda cheated (he was my favorite character), but he did say a few things he shouldn't have said. I know Nina was in love with Steve, but he didn't deserve a second chance. It especially bothered me how he said his new girlfriend reminds him a lot of Nina and wears her hair kinda the same way she does, and thinks telling her that is going to make her feel better. To me, that shows that he can just replace her with any person and be just as satisfied. It also shows that if he used a replacement Nina, he obviously isn't seeing how unique she is because he thinks he sees everything in the new girl as he did in Nina. And then now that he's broken up with his new girlfriend, he wants to go back to Nina?! It's like now she's just the side girlfriend that he only hooks up with when he's not busy dating someone else! And she's supposed to forgive him and go back to loving him just because they're going to college together and she thinks he feels sorry and bad about what he did? If he felt those things, he woudn't have done them in the first place! That just bothers me. She should've stayed with Parker. I mean, yes, besides the fact that Steve broke up with Nina for a girl just like her and that he was saving the world while they were apart, he was a bad boyfriend. He never called or e-mailed Nina and just took her for granted, thinking he could do whatever he wanted because his girlfriend was across the country and was too loyal to leave him no matter what he did. Parker was always there to listen to her problems, hang out with her, they had fun together, he was really loyal to her, and he stayed with her and did what she wanted as a not-boyfriend (even though he REALLY liked her) without crossing any lines. Nina never really realized this, and she should've. This may sound like I didn't like the book, but I actually thought it was pretty good. There were just a few things that bothered me a lot.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14643545149161054472" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


