    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4062487649" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4062487649" />
    <a title="Amelia" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/111796588-amelia"><img alt="Amelia" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1589911765p2/111796588.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4062487649?book_show_action=true">Jun 16, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Amelia" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Amelia" href="/user/show/111796588-amelia">Amelia</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4062487649" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12973784869674621200">Quick Warning: This is going to be a pretty spoilery review. I&apos;m just going to be sharing my thoughts on the whole book, without any concern for keeping it spoiler free, because it&apos;s nearly impossible to make some of the points I want to make without giving things away. I will put the whole thing in spoiler tags underneath this, but, as you can see from my rating, I don&apos;t really recommend this, so if you feel like you&apos;re never going to read this, you can read on.<br/><br/><a class='jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction'>(view spoiler)</a><span class='spoilerContainer' style='display: none'>[ So... like I said</span></span>
  <span id="freeText12973784869674621200" style="display:none">Quick Warning: This is going to be a pretty spoilery review. I'm just going to be sharing my thoughts on the whole book, without any concern for keeping it spoiler free, because it's nearly impossible to make some of the points I want to make without giving things away. I will put the whole thing in spoiler tags underneath this, but, as you can see from my rating, I don't really recommend this, so if you feel like you're never going to read this, you can read on.<br /><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ So... like I said above, didn't love this one. When I first started, I wasn't feeling into it, so I put it down, read a different book, and finished that one pretty quickly, so I figured I'd come back to this. And for most of the book it felt like a solid 3 star rating, but the ending was vastly disappointing, and the more I think back to the rest of the book, I realized that I didn't really enjoy it either.<br /><br />Before I start talking about the things I didn't love about this book, I want to talk about some pros. First of all, there's(what seems to be) pretty good LGBTQ+ representation. As someone who is straight and cis, I can't fully speak on how accurate the rep in this is. I'm also not sure what the authors background is, so I don't know what perspective she's writing this from. A pretty big focus with this is the girls struggling with their sexuality. Mel is pretty certain, and it just takes that one kiss for her to admit it to herself, but she still has some growth throughout the book where she learns what it means to her to be a lesbian, and grows into that aspect of herself. There's also a pretty maddening scene, where, after an accidental forced outing, her mom says some pretty terrible things to her(no slurs, though, but she does kind of disown her, which could be triggering). Avery, however, is much more unsure in her new attraction to girls, and spends the whole book trying to figure it out. She has some very complicated feelings, and again, I don't think I can really speak to this, but it seemed fairly authentic. <br /><br />The other main pro is Parker. Parker was the best character in this book, and really, the only reason worth reading it. He's a genuinely nice, kind, and funny human being, but is kind of treated terribly throughout the book. He also didn't have much depth, which was more about the writing.<br /><br />Now the cons-I think my biggest one would have to be the characters. First off, I was nearly halfway through the book when I started being able to recognize their personalities, and who was who, but even writing this review, I've mistakenly mixed up their names a couple of times. The characters all felt flat and bland. They have a few personality traits, and their main conflict, but nothing really defining. It kind of feels like the author fills out one of those character writing sheets that you do in elementary school, and added nothing to it. <br /><i>Avery: Likes piano, smoking and mustard<br />Dislikes her job and being gay<br />Has two brothers</i><br />And then that's it! I felt like I couldn't connect to the characters at all, I didn't feel any emotions with them, and honestly, didn't care wether or not Avery got into the music college. This expanded to the side characters as well, and the smaller their role in the story, the less defined they got, which does make sense, but because I think we were starting at such a low point for the main characters, it became more of a problem. For example, Devon: he wears ties. And is maybe smart? That's really all I know about him. And he was one of the more important ones; there was some sort of subplot with him and Nina maybe having a thing, but it was never really resolved.<br /><br />Which brings me to my next big issue. Nothing in this book was tied up neatly. The ending was grossly(as in, hugely, not, I was physically repulsed) disappointing. All these loose ends were either left hanging, or tied up in a haphazard way that left me feeling unsatisfied and annoyed. For example(and please correct me if I'm wrong here): <i><b>MEL NEVER FOUND OUT ABOUT AVERY CHEATING ON HER</b></i>! For context, Nina walked in on Avery cheating on Mel with Gaz(I think that was his name), some guy in some band she's in. Now, we later realize that this is because of her confusion about her sexuality, but still, cheating is NOT ok, in any circumstance. And then Nina COVERS FOR HER, presumably because she doesn't want to mess up the delicate balance of awkward friendship that the three fall into after she returns, but that's still really annoying. Instead, Nina gives Avery a stern talking to, but later she makes out with Gaz again, and continues to do it for a hot while. Oh, and then she makes Nina BREAK UP WITH MEL, FOR HER! I understand that there are a lot of complicated feelings, but a lot of what Avery does is not ok, and she never suffers the consequences. A few other loose ends: Parker. It's implied that they set Parker up with Scarf Girl, someone from the music college audition(don't know what college it was, sorry). And this is after Mel breaks up with him to get back together with her hippie boyfriend, who CHEATED ON HER(they were in a long distance relationship, and he comes up with a bunch of phony excuses, but still, not ok). Parker cares about her, and tries to prevent her from getting back together with Steve(hippie dude), and she ignores him, again, totally mistreating him. Steve, by the way, REALLY sucks; after cheating on Nina for 2 months, then dumping her with very little fanfare and leaving her broken in pieces, he comes crawling back to her(on her BIRTHDAY, no less), and the excuse he gives for cheating on her is that the other girl had SIMILAR HAIR! Steve is disgusting.<br /><br />Now, I'm going to try to end this, because it appears I went on a bit of a rant, and now this review is really long. I've also realized that I disliked this book more than I originally thought, so I'm lowering the rating to 1 star. Cheating with 0 consequences is NEVER ok, and that's basically all that happens in this book. Final word: As a good friend once told me, "So many problems in books could be solved if they just TALKED to each other" and that's definitely true for this one. If they'd talked, maybe they wouldn't be CHEATING on each other all the time. Remember: don't cheat. Ok, bye.<br /><br /><br /> <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span></span>
  <a data-text-id="12973784869674621200" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


